    "body_text": [
        {
            "text": "There will be patients who need to be seen and treated urgently. Services should continue to be provided, where possible, to patients at high risk of visual loss without treatment. This may include people with the conditions such as these18,22:",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 238,
                    "end": 240,
                    "mention": "18",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF9"
                },
                {
                    "start": 241,
                    "end": 243,
                    "mention": "22",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF14"
                }
            ],
            "section": "Patients needing urgent or emergency care ::: 1. Cease providing any routine eye services other than urgent or emergency care",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "Whether it is appropriate for patients to be seen for urgent/emergency eye care will depend on the individual patient, the risk of significant harm if treatment is delayed and the situation of the eye care provider. Having only one seeing eye would be a strong factor in favour of a patient being seen, for example. If possible, patients should stay away from eye health care settings if they are older than 70 years, have serious pre-existing health problems, or are immunosuppressed.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "Patients needing urgent or emergency care ::: 1. Cease providing any routine eye services other than urgent or emergency care",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "Table 1 gives some guidance on triaging patients and the appropriate precautions to take.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "Patients needing urgent or emergency care ::: 1. Cease providing any routine eye services other than urgent or emergency care",
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 0,
                    "end": 7,
                    "mention": "Table 1",
                    "ref_id": "TABREF0"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Symptoms of cough, fever, shortness of breath or flu-like symptoms are typical in COVID-19, but others are also common, including loss of taste and smell.23 It is vital to inform patients and health care workers with symptoms of COVID-19 that they should not come to the hospital or clinic, but should self-isolate (i.e., stay at home and avoid contact with other members of the household) for seven days. The United Kingdom's National Health Service (NHS) guidelines state that people who still have a high temperature after 7 days of self-isolation must remain at home until their temperature returns to normal.24",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 154,
                    "end": 156,
                    "mention": "23",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF15"
                },
                {
                    "start": 613,
                    "end": 615,
                    "mention": "24",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF16"
                }
            ],
            "section": "Symptoms & when to self-isolate ::: 2. Protect health care workers",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "The incubation period for COVID-19 is thought to range from 1 to 14 days, with symptom onset typically around 5 days; these estimates will be updated as more data becomes available.4\nPatients may be infectious before showing any symptoms, and some may show no symptoms at all. A person who has been in contact with someone known to have COVID-19 should self-isolate for 14 days, until such time as WHO guidance is updated.4 It is important to follow national guidelines. Communicate this information to patients as early as possible, so that patients who need to self-isolate do not travel to the unit in the first place. If they do arrive at the unit, there should be very clear information to prevent infection spread; e.g., telling patients to return home and self-isolate (Figure 1).",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 181,
                    "end": 182,
                    "mention": "4",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF28"
                },
                {
                    "start": 422,
                    "end": 423,
                    "mention": "4",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF28"
                }
            ],
            "section": "Symptoms & when to self-isolate ::: 2. Protect health care workers",
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 777,
                    "end": 785,
                    "mention": "Figure 1",
                    "ref_id": "FIGREF1"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Table 2 provides more detailed guidance on the type of PPE to be worn. It is important to take note of national guidelines. PPE is likely to include disposable gloves, disposable gown, face respirator mask (when appropriate, e.g., FFP3 or N95) and eye protection. Follow strict PPE wearing and removing procedures (see panel). Dispose of PPE appropriately and carry out thorough room cleaning and air exchange after each patient.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "Symptoms & when to self-isolate ::: 2. Protect health care workers",
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 0,
                    "end": 7,
                    "mention": "Table 2",
                    "ref_id": "TABREF1"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Aerosol-generating procedures (AGPs). Aspects relevant to ophthalmology are in bold:",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "Symptoms & when to self-isolate ::: 2. Protect health care workers",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "Defer surgical procedures where possible. If surgery cannot be avoided, this should be done under local anaesthesia if possible, taking full precautions. General anaesthesia is an \u2018aerosol-generating procedure\u2019 (AGP) which creates a high-risk environment for virus transmission. However, even surgery under local anaesthesia will involve significant exposure between medical personnel and patient and should be considered high risk. If surgery must be undertaken, then full PPE should be used for all patients.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "Symptoms & when to self-isolate ::: 2. Protect health care workers",
            "ref_spans": []
        }
    ],
